ce:section.ce:para:
CDs have gradually become a potential substitute for traditional noble metal catalysts due to their good electrical conductivity and high stability, and their ability to improve the electrocatalytic performance by doping heteroatoms (nitrogen, phosphorus, etc.). By combining porous materials with CDs, it is possible to effectively prevent the aggregation of CDs and provide more active sites, thereby exhibiting more excellent electrocatalytic performance. For example, Zhang et al. [80] prepared N-CNDs@MCNSs composites for oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) by coating CNDs on acid-treated microporous carbon nanospheres. Individual N-CNDs could not form stable electrocatalyst films for ORR catalysis because of their high-water dispersion property. However, N-CNDs@MCNSs as ORR electrocatalysts coated on bare GC electrode can exhibit high electrocatalytic activity with an onset potential of −0.08 V that is very close to that of the Pt/C catalyst (−0.05 V) and showed a four-electron ORR process. Under the same stability test conditions, the N-CNDs@MCNSs coated electrode had a higher retention of catalytic activity (over 90%) than the Pt/C coated GC electrode (76%). NDs/MCNSs exhibit high ORR catalytic activity and better operational stability because MCNSs can stabilize and disperse N-CNDs to improve the electrocatalytic performance. CDs self-modified nitrogen, sulfur co-doped porous carbon composites (CDs/NSPC) were designed by Liang et al. as an another electrocatalyst for ORR catalysis [74]. The rich edges of CDs confer catalytic activity for ORR, heteroatom doping can further enhance the catalytic activity, and the porous structure of CDs/NSPCs can provide more active sites. As a result, This electrocatalyst exhibited remarkable ORR catalytic performance in an alkaline medium (O2 saturated 0.1 M KOH) with an onset potential of 0.975 V and half-wave potential of 0.840 V, a Tafel slope of 77.4 mV dec-1, and the electron transfer number of 3.94, outperforming Pt/C (0.970 V, 0.840 V, 87.9 mV dec-1 and 3.96), NSPC (0.930 V, 0.820 V, 101.7 mV dec-1 and 3.89), and NSC (0.816 V, 0.670 V, 103.1 mV dec-1 and 2.82), as shown in Fig. 18
                           . Recently, Shin et al. [86] prepared carbon-based bifunctional electrocatalysts (NS-CD@gf) for ORR and OER via hydrothermal method and annealing treatment. Optimal NS-CD@gf can possess ORR activities superior to that of conventional Pt/C and OER activities equivalent to Ir/C (Fig. 19
                           ). It is found that the ORR and OER activities of NS-CD@gf were derived from heteroatom functional groups of CDs, and porous carbon frameworks could facilitate the transport of oxygen molecules, both of which synergistically improved the electrocatalytic performance.
